Pre-heat your oven to 200 degrees and bring a #pot{} of @water{} to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Halve the @potato{2} and when the water is boiling, place them in your pot for ~{10%minutes} to cook. Then drain them and pop them on a #chopping board{}.

Place the flat edges of your potatoes on a board and make deep cuts into the curved top of each potato. Arrange your potatoes in an #ovenproof dish{}, drizzle with @oil{4%tbsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good grind of @black pepper{}. Shake your dish to make sure they get a good coating of everything! Pop on the top shelf of your oven for ~{25-30%minutes} until crisp and brown.

While your potatoes are cooking, get on with the pork! Heat @olive oil{1 1/2%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} and fry the @pork medallion{4} for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side, turning once until each piece is nicely browned.

> Don't wash your pan up, you'll need it later for the apple sauce!

Pop the pork on a #baking tray{}, generously grind over some black pepper and cover with a sheet of #foil{}. Cook for a further ~{8-10%minutes} in your oven until cooked through. The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Lift out, wrap loosely in foil to rest and set aside until everything else is ready.

> Resting the meat ensures it is lovely and juicy.

Put a pot of water on to boil (you can use the same pot you cooked your potatoes in!) and slice the @Chantenay carrots{2} in half lengthways (no need to peel!). Cook them in boiling water for ~{5-6%minutes}, until just tender.

While your carrots are cooking, quarter, peel and core the @Cox's apple{2}. Cut into 1cm thick slices. Add to the pan you were cooking your pork in with the meat juices (no need to wash!), add the @honey{4%tbsp}, @vegetable stock pot{1}, @apple and sage jelly{1} and @water{100%ml}, simmer for ~{5%minutes}, until the apples are softened.

Thickly slice your pork and serve with your potatoes and carrots. Spoon your apple and honey sauce over and enjoy.